</p><p>For this reason, many mathematical textbooks only consider the case that the infinite sum given above <a href="/wiki/Absolute_convergence" title="Absolute convergence">converges absolutely</a>, which implies that the infinite sum is a finite number independent of the ordering of summands.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section&#95;IX.2&#95;14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section_IX.2-14"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>14<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> In the alternative case that the infinite sum does not converge absolutely, one says the random variable <i>does not have finite expectation.</i><sup id="cite&#95;ref-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section&#95;IX.2&#95;14-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section_IX.2-14"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>14<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
