</p><p>There is a rigorous mathematical theory underlying such ideas, which is often taken as part of the definition of the Lebesgue integral.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-FOOTNOTEBillingsley1995Section&#95;15&#95;19-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBillingsley1995Section_15-19"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>19<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The first fundamental observation is that, whichever of the above definitions are followed, any <i>nonnegative</i> random variable whatsoever can be given an unambiguous expected value; whenever absolute convergence fails, then the expected value can be defined as <span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle +\infty }">
