<p><a href="/wiki/Concentration_inequalities" class="mw-redirect" title="Concentration inequalities">Concentration inequalities</a> control the likelihood of a random variable taking on large values. <a href="/wiki/Markov%27s_inequality" title="Markov&#39;s inequality">Markov's inequality</a> is among the best-known and simplest to prove: for a <i>nonnegative</i> random variable <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">X</span> and any positive number <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">a</span>, it states that<sup id="cite&#95;ref-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section&#95;IX.6Feller1971Section&#95;V.7PapoulisPillai2002Section&#95;5-4Ross2019Section&#95;2.8&#95;37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section_IX.6Feller1971Section_V.7PapoulisPillai2002Section_5-4Ross2019Section_2.8-37"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>37<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> <span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle \operatorname {P} (X\geq a)\leq {\frac {\operatorname {E} [X]}{a}}.}">
