where <span class="texhtml">Var</span> is the <a href="/wiki/Variance" title="Variance">variance</a>.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section&#95;IX.6Feller1971Section&#95;V.7PapoulisPillai2002Section&#95;5-4Ross2019Section&#95;2.8&#95;37-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section_IX.6Feller1971Section_V.7PapoulisPillai2002Section_5-4Ross2019Section_2.8-37"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>37<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> These inequalities are significant for their nearly complete lack of conditional assumptions. For example, for any random variable with finite expectation, the Chebyshev inequality implies that there is at least a 75% probability of an outcome being within two <a href="/wiki/Standard_deviation" title="Standard deviation">standard deviations</a> of the expected value. However, in special cases the Markov and Chebyshev inequalities often give much weaker information than is otherwise available. For example, in the case of an unweighted dice, Chebyshev's inequality says that odds of rolling between 1 and 6 is at least 53%; in reality, the odds are of course 100%.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section&#95;IX.6&#95;38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section_IX.6-38"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>38<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Kolmogorov_inequality" class="mw-redirect" title="Kolmogorov inequality">Kolmogorov inequality</a> extends the Chebyshev inequality to the context of sums of random variables.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section&#95;IX.7&#95;39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFeller1968Section_IX.7-39"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>39<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
