<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Beta_first_moment.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Beta_first_moment.svg/250px-Beta_first_moment.svg.png" decoding="async" width="250" height="170" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Beta_first_moment.svg/500px-Beta_first_moment.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="308" data-file-height="210" /></a><figcaption>The mass of probability distribution is balanced at the expected value, here a Beta(α,β) distribution with expected value α/(α+β).</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Classical_mechanics" title="Classical mechanics">classical mechanics</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Center_of_mass" title="Center of mass">center of mass</a> is an analogous concept to expectation. For example, suppose <i>X</i> is a discrete random variable with values <i>x<sub>i</sub></i> and corresponding probabilities <i>p<sub>i</sub>.</i> Now consider a weightless rod on which are placed weights, at locations <i>x<sub>i</sub></i> along the rod and having masses <i>p<sub>i</sub></i> (whose sum is one). The point at which the rod balances is E[<i>X</i>].
